  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Supporting workbench · language to causal graph
    </div>
    <h1>MiniCausalLang — language structure with a known answer</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      A small workbench for turning grammatical structure into causal variables and licensed inferences.
    </p>

    <p>
      MiniCausalLang is the workbench that makes the program's central question operational: how
      does linguistic structure support inference, and does a model actually use that structure? It
      gives small grammars whose sentences are generated from a known causal/inferential graph, so
      structure recovery, <a href="/research/isotrace">Isotrace</a>-style path localization, and
      CIY-style quantitative grading can be tested against a known target.
    </p>

    <MiniCausalFigure />

    <p>
      The hard direction in my <a href="/writing/inferential-productivity">note on inferential
      productivity</a> is reverse: given a behavior, what is the <em>smallest</em> causal structure
      that has to be there? On a real model, there is usually no ground truth against which to score
      a recovered structure. MiniCausalLang keeps the bridge explicit before trusting the method
      elsewhere: specify the grammar, compile it into a causal graph, enumerate the inferences that
      graph licenses, train or evaluate a model on that data, and test whether behavioral recovery
      returns the structure that was actually planted.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is supporting infrastructure, not a fourth equal core paper. It exists to make the link
      between linguistic form, causal structure, and inferential yield explicit enough to be
      falsifiable against a known answer.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive workbench — specify a grammar, compile the graph, see what recovery returns — will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
